<figcaption class="attribution">
        <span class="attribution__caption">There are currently about 85 students from 13 states and Puerto Rico enrolled at Shrub Oak.</span>
    
        <span class="attribution__credit">
        <span class="a11y">Credit: </span>
        Liz Moughon/ProPublica
    </span>
    
    
    </figcaption>


</figure>

        
    
                    
<hr>
</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="66.0">Last October, soon after the school day ended, a Shrub Oak employee began menacing a student who was yelling, court records show. The man raised a desk over his head and threatened to throw it at the 22-year-old student from Chicago.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="67.0">He also knocked on the student’s forehead with his knuckles four or five times “similar to a way a person would knock very hard on a door,” according to the sworn statement of an employee who said she witnessed the incident.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="68.0">The student said, “Ouch, you are hurting me,” according to that statement, and the student at one point grabbed the right side of her stomach and cried out that she’d been hit.</p>

<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="68.1">The employee was fired then charged with three misdemeanors — menacing, harassment and endangering the welfare of a disabled person. He has pleaded not guilty.</p>
        
    
                    

<figure
    data-pp-id="69"
    data-pp-blocktype="image"
    class="bb-image size11 center  wide-sm wrap 
                ">

    


                    
    


