        srcset="https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Plane-001.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=267&amp;q=75&amp;w=400&amp;s=f7c39b006078b78279c5248ef8b9a687 400w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Plane-001.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=534&amp;q=75&amp;w=800&amp;s=ce98f30be2e30fe866aeb827661ecf12 800w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Plane-001.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=800&amp;q=75&amp;w=1200&amp;s=30c2f37fd830c80c37e4351a6f59b70c 1200w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Plane-001.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=867&amp;q=75&amp;w=1300&amp;s=3a9c73d221c85420715737fb39714fb0 1300w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Plane-001.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=967&amp;q=75&amp;w=1450&amp;s=f9022656482df79ac6c9ba8743aabfed 1450w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Plane-001.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1067&amp;q=75&amp;w=1600&amp;s=8191753566571d074248d991339bef35 1600w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Plane-001.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1334&amp;q=75&amp;w=2000&amp;s=517f14878462ae3bd31a78179cdf07be 2000w"
                    />

            
    
<figcaption class="attribution">
        <span class="attribution__caption">A 22-year-old student attended Shrub Oak until late last year when her family brought her home to Chicago.</span>
    
        <span class="attribution__credit">
        <span class="a11y">Credit: </span>
        Taylor Glascock, special to ProPublica
    </span>
    
    
    </figcaption>

</figure>

        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="74.0">The October incident was one of the more than 150 times that the local police responded to calls about the school since 2019 — from employees reporting student injuries to parents asking for well-being checks on their children.</p>
        
    
                        <aside class="bb-ad full | hide-print">
        <div class="htlad-inline-2"></div>
    </aside>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="76.0">In at least four other incidents involving suspected abuse, Shrub Oak told police that it had fired employees, records show. The school fired an employee in 2022 who was seen shoving a student “to the floor multiple times.” It fired another employee in November 2023 after a co-worker saw him hit a student in the head and chest and slam him to the floor.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="77.0">In February of last year, Shrub Oak also fired a worker who reportedly punched two students in the stomach at night in their bedrooms. The school told police about the incident three days later. An employee who witnessed the incident told police he saw the worker punch both students and then justify it, saying, “Sometimes you have to (motioned punching) to get them to do what they have to do,” according to court records.</p>
        
    
                        <figure
        data-pp-id="78"
        data-pp-blocktype="audio"
        class="bb-audio size04 right out02 wide-sm wrap
             bb--border-top             hide-print
            ">

        
<div class="lead-in">
            <p class="lead-in__title" id="listen-to-a-911-call-related-to-the-november-2023-incident">Listen to a 911 Call Related to the November 2023 Incident</p>
        </div>


        <audio class="bb-audio__player" controls src="https://assets-d.propublica.org/v5/audio/Shrub-Oak-911-Call.mp3"></audio>
        
        
<figcaption class="attribution">
        <span class="attribution__caption">A security guard alerts authorities to the incident.</span>
    
        <span class="attribution__credit">
        <span class="a11y">Credit: </span>
        Yorktown Police Department. Edited by ProPublica for clarity and to preserve anonymity.
    </span>
    
    
    </figcaption>


    </figure>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="79.0">The employee in the February incident was arrested, but the Westchester County district attorney’s office said it dismissed the case because of issues with gathering sufficient evidence within the required time frame for criminal cases.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="80.0">The school told ProPublica that it calls the police to be transparent and impartial, and that some students make false allegations or call 911 as “negative attention-seeking behavior.”</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="81.0">Underlying many of the problems at Shrub Oak are staffing shortages, according to records and interviews. An internal email shows that one night, a “skeleton staff” was stretched too thin to attend to students’ hygiene. Employees provided ProPublica schedules that showed multiple students assigned to one worker even though the students required individual aides and the districts were paying for them.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="82.0">Shrub Oak acknowledged the challenge of operating round-the-clock, but its spokesperson said that its staff of 400 is adequate and that the school “determines staffing levels based on student needs and contract parameters.” The school said that some students have advanced to where they can work without individual aides and that it passes any savings onto the districts.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="83.0">James Roddy, a former Shrub Oak student, said the school sometimes was so short on staff “they’d literally ask other kids to watch over them.” He and another student ran away from the school one evening in January 2022 and spent the night hiding inside a Home Depot, police records show.</p>
        
    
                    

<figure
    data-pp-id="84"
    data-pp-blocktype="image"
    class="bb-image size13 center  wide-sm wrap 
                ">

    


                    
    


    <img
        class=""
        alt=""
        width="3000"
        height="2001"
        loading="lazy" js-autosizes        src="https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak0222_maxWidth_3000_maxHeight_3000_ppi_72_quality_95_embedColorProfile_true.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=534&amp;q=75&amp;w=800&amp;s=bdbebe6c4339e3198944a60f4b1aa657"
        srcset="https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak0222_maxWidth_3000_maxHeight_3000_ppi_72_quality_95_embedColorProfile_true.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=267&amp;q=75&amp;w=400&amp;s=80719ebf55bca6fad939a8095a11bfc5 400w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak0222_maxWidth_3000_maxHeight_3000_ppi_72_quality_95_embedColorProfile_true.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=534&amp;q=75&amp;w=800&amp;s=bdbebe6c4339e3198944a60f4b1aa657 800w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak0222_maxWidth_3000_maxHeight_3000_ppi_72_quality_95_embedColorProfile_true.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=800&amp;q=75&amp;w=1200&amp;s=9bce8b3526a4826edeff9b138a916585 1200w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak0222_maxWidth_3000_maxHeight_3000_ppi_72_quality_95_embedColorProfile_true.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=867&amp;q=75&amp;w=1300&amp;s=40b024b984b52a9d6119563ab58064f8 1300w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak0222_maxWidth_3000_maxHeight_3000_ppi_72_quality_95_embedColorProfile_true.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=967&amp;q=75&amp;w=1450&amp;s=227f157c2c4ab4f2bdf4fa16e776bd8e 1450w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak0222_maxWidth_3000_maxHeight_3000_ppi_72_quality_95_embedColorProfile_true.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1067&amp;q=75&amp;w=1600&amp;s=002690547c54073c50d3ff0bb1578eac 1600w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak0222_maxWidth_3000_maxHeight_3000_ppi_72_quality_95_embedColorProfile_true.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1334&amp;q=75&amp;w=2000&amp;s=8903c0042a771673145c1394acac11e4 2000w"
                    />

            
    
<figcaption class="attribution">
        <span class="attribution__caption">James Roddy, 18, is a former Shrub Oak student who lives in Utah.</span>
    
        <span class="attribution__credit">
        <span class="a11y">Credit: </span>
        Kim Raff for ProPublica
    </span>
    
    
    </figcaption>

</figure>

        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="85.0">Despite being a school that pledges to help students with intense behavioral challenges, Shrub Oak has only one certified behavioral therapist, employees and parents told ProPublica. Shrub Oak would not confirm the number.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="86.0">“You send your kid to a residential school because you can’t handle all the things they need,” said the mother of one current student. “So they go to a school where they will have a team of experts, and you trust that the school will provide that. They are not providing that.”</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="87.0">A current employee described his concern over a student who was isolated in his bedroom as punishment. Like the Ashinoffs, he found he had nowhere to turn. He tried the state Education Department and the Justice Center, which investigates allegations that students with disabilities have been abused or neglected. He said both agencies told him they had no authority over unapproved schools.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="88.0">“It broke my heart,” the employee said. “Who is watching out for these students?”</p>
        
    
                    

<figure
    data-pp-id="89"
    data-pp-blocktype="image"
    class="bb-image size06 center  wide-sm wrap 
                ">

    


                    
    


    <img
        class=""
        alt=""
        width="1003"
        height="869"
        loading="lazy" js-autosizes        src="https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Email.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=693&amp;q=80&amp;w=800&amp;s=9fa88fcf30d081f36042360f3b3d1340"
        srcset="https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Email.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=347&amp;q=80&amp;w=400&amp;s=964d37ffb75a439cd6cccdc392918f5c 400w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Email.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=693&amp;q=80&amp;w=800&amp;s=9fa88fcf30d081f36042360f3b3d1340 800w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Email.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1040&amp;q=80&amp;w=1200&amp;s=ad799c51ed0f59edd4403ef05f2e46ab 1200w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Email.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1126&amp;q=80&amp;w=1300&amp;s=5c9099d7d17d4510e68c5606daa0c994 1300w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Email.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1256&amp;q=80&amp;w=1450&amp;s=c6dd42ebf209538e17e28ddc227ca387 1450w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Email.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1386&amp;q=80&amp;w=1600&amp;s=19c218c845a077490368c0dbfc55c91d 1600w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Email.png?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1733&amp;q=80&amp;w=2000&amp;s=61ca0253302ec3ae4ca4225946150dda 2000w"
                    />

            
    
<figcaption class="attribution">
        <span class="attribution__caption">A note from Shrub Oak’s staff messaging system describes a student’s condition.</span>
    
        <span class="attribution__credit">
        <span class="a11y">Credit: </span>
        Obtained by ProPublica. Redactions by ProPublica.
    </span>
    
    
    </figcaption>

</figure>

        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="90.0">Other workers and parents expressed their alarm at failures to address students’ basic needs: medicine, hygiene and food.</p>
        
    
                        <aside class="bb-ad full | hide-print">
        <div class="htlad-inline-2"></div>
    </aside>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="92.0">“I had a student almost die because he had a seizure and almost stopped breathing. They had stopped giving him medicine,” said a former behavior specialist at the school. Police records and emails describe students taking the wrong medication or none at all. Shrub Oak told ProPublica that it has changed its medication practices.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="93.0">Several parents also said their children uncharacteristically began urinating and defecating in their rooms because they were locked out of bathrooms overnight. Shrub Oak said some students have conditions that lead them to soil themselves — sometimes intentionally — and that staff are always available to let students in the locked bathrooms.</p>
        
    
                    

<figure
    data-pp-id="94"
    data-pp-blocktype="image"
    class="bb-image size03 right out02 wide-sm wrap 
                ">

    


                    
    


    <img
        class=""
        alt=""
        width="3024"
        height="4032"
        loading="lazy" js-autosizes        src="https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Food.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1067&amp;q=75&amp;w=800&amp;s=45822839cfd42af304f641d23c9a7b13"
        srcset="https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Food.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=533&amp;q=75&amp;w=400&amp;s=018f2f4bb6e8bbe10ec6bf7dcfa620ba 400w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Food.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1067&amp;q=75&amp;w=800&amp;s=45822839cfd42af304f641d23c9a7b13 800w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Food.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1600&amp;q=75&amp;w=1200&amp;s=43374cf2811e705043781261f83c24da 1200w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Food.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1733&amp;q=75&amp;w=1300&amp;s=a9bd449c03e3cde30e4e889b226483d8 1300w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Food.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1933&amp;q=75&amp;w=1450&amp;s=14ce3694bab4511af4a9732c6a2f49a3 1450w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Food.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=2133&amp;q=75&amp;w=1600&amp;s=c8fa065546c8221d43989ffb7aeabd7d 1600w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/Shrub-Oak-Food.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=2667&amp;q=75&amp;w=2000&amp;s=5883b05f1db6b7074cffc6675f5e5d14 2000w"
                    />

            
    
<figcaption class="attribution">
        <span class="attribution__caption">A student eats his takeout meal at Shrub Oak.</span>
    
        <span class="attribution__credit">
        <span class="a11y">Credit: </span>
        Obtained by ProPublica from the family
    </span>
    
    
    </figcaption>

</figure>

        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="95.0">And for years, Shrub Oak leaders have been telling parents that a “restaurant-quality kitchen” would be finished “by year end” or in a few months, records show.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="96.0">Instead, the food mostly comes from a nearby deli, though the school says Shrub Oak’s chef and nutritionist “are beyond compare.” (The therapy pool and equestrian stable also have not been built.) Shrub Oak told ProPublica on April 12 that the kitchen is slated to open “within days,” pending completion of electrical work. As of Tuesday, the kitchen still was not open.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="97.0">“The promise of this place was magic,” one mother from California said. She pulled her son from Shrub Oak last year and sent him to an approved residential school for autistic students.</p>

<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="97.1">“Why they’re even allowed to have a school, I have no idea,” she said.</p>
        
    
                    

<figure
    data-pp-id="98"
    data-pp-blocktype="video-self-hosted"
    class="bb-video-self-hosted size13 center  wide-sm wrap
